Date: Wed 20 Jul 2005
From: Stephen Toovey <toovey@travelclinic.co.za>

A comment on transmission of infection
--------------------------------------
[Dr Toovey's comment refers specifically to the observation contained in
part (4) of Richard Frankel's comments in "Respiratory infections, fatal,
gorillas - Africa (02)," stating that "CDC uses 3 feet as a guideline for
droplet transmission. Aerosol transmission is unlikely outdoors. Even if
one were concerned about aerosol transmission, one airplane study of
tuberculosis suggested that the risk is small more than 2 rows from the
index case." - Mod.CP]
Without commenting specifically on the risk of gorillas being infected by
human visitors, it is probably misleading to extrapolate from studies on
the transmission of TB and other droplet spread infections in pressurized
civilian passenger aircraft. These aircraft typically distribute air in the
passenger compartment in a laminar flow pattern, effectively limiting
distribution, unlike the situation in a near contact with a gorilla. See: A
Mangili, MA Gendreau. Transmission of infectious diseases during commercial
air travel. Lancet 2005; 365: 989-96.
--
Dr Stephen Toovey MBBCh, CTM, FACTM, FFTM
Johannesburg South Africa, and Basel Switzerland
Burggartenstrasse 32, CH-4103 Bottmingen
