[3]
Date: Mon 20 Jul 2005
From: Liz Williamson <e.a.williamson@stir.ac.uk>

re: recommended separation distance
-----------------------------------
I wish to respond to an issue raised in the post: "Respiratory infections,
fatal, gorillas - Africa (02) 20050719.2083." One of the questions asked by
Richard I Frankel in his comment on "Respiratory infections, fatal,
gorillas - Africa" is that: "The 7 meter distance is announced but not
observed. We were certainly closer than that much of the time. But what is
magic about 7 meters?"
For many years, the regulation distance to be maintained between gorillas
and tourists (and researchers) was 5 meters. In 1999, Jaco Homsy, MD, MPH,
carried out a Critical Review of the Rules and Regulations Governing Park
Management and Tourism for the Wild Mountain Gorilla, _Gorilla gorilla
beringei_. One of the recommendations resulting from this study was that
this distance should be increased to 7 meters: Dr Homsy's report, "Ape
Tourism And Human Diseases: How Close Should We Get?" can be downloaded
from the website of the International Gorilla Conservation Programme:
<http://www.mountaingorillas.org/our_work/our_work.asp>
--
Liz Williamson, PhD
Department of Psychology
University of Stirling
Stirling FK9 4LA
Scotland
UK
[This is the same document referred to by Dr Stenvers in the preceding
comment. It is an 86 page document that deals comprehensively with the risk
of spread of human disease to apes and, among other things, tabulates known
information on the susceptibility of apes to human viruses and vice versa.
The content is too detailed to summarize adequately here, and interested
readers should refer to the original text - Mod.CP]
See Also
